        // === THEORY ===
        theory(1, "Our Environment",
            "How would you explain the term 'Environment' to your study group?\nIn what four ways are water bodies in your community polluted?\nSuggest four workable ways by which water bodies in your community can be made safe for use.",
            "(a) Definition of Environment:\nEnvironment refers to the entire physical and social surroundings of an individual, including living and non-living elements (plants, animals, soil, water, air, buildings, and human culture) that influence human life.\n\n(b) Four ways water bodies are polluted:\n1. Galamsey: Illegal small-scale mining washes mud, heavy mercury, and cyanide directly into local riverbeds.\n2. Household Liquid/Solid Waste: Throwing sewage, plastic bottles, and organic refuse directly into streams.\n3. Agricultural Runoff: Washing chemical weedicides, pesticides, and inorganic fertilizers from farms into water bodies during downpours.\n4. Industrial Discharge: Direct piping of untreated toxic liquid chemicals and manufacturing wastes into rivers.\n\n(c) Four ways to make water bodies safe for use:\n1. Strict Law Enforcement: Severely punishing illegal miners and industrial entities who pollute water bodies.\n2. Buffer Zones: Creating tree and grass buffer zones along river banks to filter farm runoff.\n3. Public Education: Sensitizing local residents on the hygienic and economic value of maintaining clean water bodies.\n4. Proper Waste Treatment: Ensuring municipal assemblies construct specialized waste processing plants to filter domestic sewage before it drains into the rivers.",
            "Environment explanation: 4 Marks\n4 Causes of pollution: 8 Marks\n4 Solutions: 8 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20),

        theory(2, "Population & Social Issues",
            "Having observed tension among the youth in your community, write to the Assemblyman explaining four ways in which tensions could be calmed down and also prevent conflicts.\nPrepare a presentation outline on how peace and security can lead to national development in Ghana.",
            "(a) Four ways to calm youth tension and prevent conflicts (Letter/Report format elements):\n1. Creating Local Employment: Providing skill acquisition programs, apprenticeships, and jobs to keep the youth productive.\n2. Dialogue and Town-hall Mediation: Organizing direct peace forums between rival youth factions and local leaders to air out grievances.\n3. Promoting Sports and Inter-group recreation: Using sports tournaments (e.g. community gala) to build friendly bridges and foster unity.\n4. Quick police response and fair justice: Ensuring local security forces act neutrally, resolve issues, and enforce laws without tribal bias.\n\n(b) Presentation outline on how peace and security lead to development:\n1. Attracting Foreign Direct Investment (FDI): Investors are highly confident to set up factories in safe, secure, and politically stable countries.\n2. Tourism Growth: International tourists visit historical castles and parks when there are no threats of conflict, boosting foreign exchange.\n3. Uninterrupted Infrastructure Projects: Construction of critical highways, hospitals, and schools proceeds smoothly without vandalization.\n4. Stable Human Capital: Citizens work and study productively, allowing schools, markets, and banks to operate at full capacity.",
            "Youth conflict prevention strategies: 12 Marks\nPeace to Development outline: 8 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20),

        theory(3, "Government & Citizenship",
            "Explain four ways by which national elections promote democracy in Ghana.\nIn what four ways can citizens contribute to the development of the state?",
            "(a) Four ways national elections promote democracy in Ghana:\n1. Peaceful Change of Power: Elections provide a legal, structured, and non-violent means for citizens to transition or change governments.\n2. Representative Governance: They allow the public to select their own preferred leaders and MPs to speak on their behalf in Parliament.\n3. Public Accountability: Unperforming leaders and politicians can be voted out of office, forcing public servants to work hard.\n4. Civic Participation: Elections educate and engage citizens in political debates, building national democratic consciousness.\n\n(b) Four ways citizens can contribute to national development:\n1. Prompt Payment of Taxes: Contributing tax revenues to fund national utilities, hospitals, and paved roads.\n2. Respecting and Defending the Constitution: Obeying national laws and cooperating with security agencies to maintain order.\n3. Hard Work and Professionalism: Executing public or private sector duties diligently to boost national economic productivity.\n4. Environmental Sanitation: Participating in local clean-up exercises and maintaining personal hygiene to prevent disease outbreaks.",
            "Elections in democracy: 12 Marks\nCitizen development contributions: 8 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20),

        theory(4, "Economy & Development",
            "Identify four challenges mostly associated with human resource development in Ghana.\nExplain four ways in which the government can use the tourism industry to drive development.",
            "(a) Four challenges of human resource development in Ghana:\n1. Inadequate Funding: Insufficient budgetary allocation to build modern technical schools, labs, and universities.\n2. Outdated School Curricula: Focus on passive theoretical learning rather than active, hands-on science and technology (STEM).\n3. Brain Drain: Migration of highly skilled Ghanaian doctors, nurses, and engineers to western countries for higher pay.\n4. Poor working environment: Absence of modern tools, research facilities, and medical gear makes workers inefficient.\n\n(b) Four ways government can use tourism to drive development:\n1. Direct Infrastructure Upgrades: Constructing paved, high-quality roads leading to remote natural tourist hubs (e.g., Wli waterfalls).\n2. Job Creation: Supporting hospitality, tour guards, car rentals, and local souvenir craft makers, lowering unemployment.\n3. Revenue and Taxation: Levying hotel and entry taxes to raise municipal and national funds for development.\n4. Global Branding: Promoting cultural events (e.g. Year of Return) to build international diplomatic and business partnerships.",
            "Human resource challenges: 12 Marks\nUsing tourism for development: 8 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20),

        theory(5, "Science & Technology",
            "Define 'technology'.\nIdentify four technological gadgets you would take on a trip to a rural village, and explain how each gadget will help you.\nList two challenges you may encounter when using technology.",
            "(a) Definition of Technology:\nTechnology is the practical application of scientific knowledge, tools, skills, and inventions to improve upon the quality of human life and solve practical day-to-day challenges.\n\n(b) Four gadgets and their uses on a rural trip:\n1. Smartphone: Enables fast communication with family, mapping routes (GPS), and recording educational photos/videos.\n2. Solar-powered Power Bank: Recharges devices since electricity supply in remote villages may be erratic or non-existent.\n3. Water Purifier Straw: Uses modern filtration technology to make river/well water instantly safe for drinking.\n4. LED Flashlight/Lantern: Provides bright illumination at night during rural walks or power outages.\n\n(c) Two challenges when using technology:\n1. High Cost: Buying, maintaining, or replacing sophisticated gadgets and internet data is very expensive.\n2. Electricity Dependence: Many modern gadgets become completely useless once their battery runs out if there is no power source.",
            "Technology definition: 2 Marks\n4 Gadgets with clear usage detail: 16 Marks\n2 Challenges listing: 2 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20)
